In this example, `IMachineWorker` is an interface that defines a set of methods that all machine workers should implement. Each specific type of machine worker (dishwasher, vacuum cleaner, etc.) then implements this interface and provides its own implementation of the methods. 

This way, you can create objects of any class that implements `IMachineWorker` and call the appropriate methods on them without knowing their exact type at compile time. This is an example of polymorphism in object-oriented programming.

