    override fun fly()  {
        println("$name soars through the air with magic!")
    }
}

class Fighter(private val name: String) : MeleeAttacker {
    private var stamina: Int = 100

    override fun meleeAttack()  {
        if (stamina >= 10) {
            println("$name swings sword with great force!")
            stamina -= 10
        } else {
            println("$name is too tired to attack!")
        }
    }
}
```
The violation here is the Interface Segregation Principle (ISP). The `GameCharacter` interface has methods for all types of actions, which are not applicable to all characters. This violates ISP because clients should not be forced to depend on interfaces they do not use. 

To fix this, we segregate the responsibilities into separate interfaces: `MeleeAttacker`, `SpellCaster`, and `Flyer`. Each character class then implements only those interfaces that it needs. This way, each interface has a single responsibility, which adheres to ISP.

